A review of the careersaas app¶

Author: Omar Safwat

Date: 12th February, 2021

Synopsis¶

The report presents a short study on the effect of introducing a new filtering feature for the careeraas portal. The new feature proposed concerns the work visa and citizenship eligibility requirements for the available job position. The portal's web search results for the position of a "Mechanical Engineer" were scraped using Pyhton to extract the number of job offers with specific citizenship and work visa requirements, thus testing for the impact of applying this feature on a job search.

Introduction¶

International job search is facilitated by careersaas' flexible app. The emphasis put by the app on WFH ("Work From Home") and remote job opportunities, is a clear invitation to every international job seeker to start using careeraas services as their primary source for their career search. When the app provides direct access to the recruiter's full profile and job website, the user, in return, is left uncrippled by unnecessary mediary stops such as; creating a new user account on a recruiters' platform to finally access the job offer. An additional filtering feature is, therefore, proposed here to further fascilitate the search of the international job seeker.

Analysis¶

The interface is clear and organized allowing for quick access to each of the search results. Results shown inside the red frame annotated by "1" are influenced by the user input inside the magenta and green coloured frames, annotated by "2" and "3", respectively. Input from box "2" matches the search results with the user's profile, while entries in the filtering box "3" narrows down the search using entries' values under the three columns: "Role", "Company", and "Location". However, the international job seeker must be redirected to the recruiter's website, in order to inspect the requirements and specifically, the citizenship and work eligibility requirements. On the other hand, websites such as linkedin would easily permit the user to glean this information quickly without being redirected, as illustrated in the figure below.

In [4]:

I propose a feature that excludes search results with specific citizenship and visa requirements to facilitate the process for intenational job seekers. Testing the effect of this feature manually among the over 1500 search result would be strenuous, therefore, I've randomly collected a limited number of 324 result entries from the available search results and web scraped them using python, to gain on a measure of the feature's effectivenes within reasonable time and computational limits. About 10% of the scraped job offers had specific visa or citizenship requirements. This would amount to somewhere around a 150 job offer out of the original 1500. The ratio may seem on the lower side, however, to the eye of the applicant this is a considerable reduction of a 150 application process, and it will definitely help aim the applicant's focus, time and energy towards more relevant job offers, and that would certainly have a positive effect over the applicant's confidence.

Further study recommendations¶

The analysis was limited by a simple web scraping routine to gain insight in a reasonable amount of time. I'd suggest implementing a more advanced and practical approach utilizing classifaction machine learning models to more accurately divide the job searches, and extract the relevant information. Moreover, the analysis was only conducted on one job title, and the results may differ for another, depending on the typical working conditions pertaining to the job title in consideration.

Abstract¶

The relevant sections of the portal's html source code were copied to a local text file for this analysis. The code below reads the text file and parses each of the randomly selected 324 job offer. The text file was uploaded on a github repository

In [ ]:
#Import bs4 for HTML parsing
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup as bs
import requests

#Retreive 'redirect' links to all job postings and store them in a list (merge later in a dataframe)
with open('jobTable2.txt') as html_file:
    jobTable = bs(html_file, 'html.parser')
    
#Isolate redirect html links to job pages
linkTags = jobTable.find_all('a')
jobURL = []
for link in linkTags:
    href_= link.get('href')
    if href_.startswith('redirect') is True:
        jobURL.append(href_)
        
#prepend the app html to 'redirect'
for i in range(len(jobURL)):
    jobURL[i] = "https://app.careersaas.com/portal/" + jobURL[i]

#For each job link look for word matches
result = []
for index, url in enumerate(jobURL):
    result.append(False)
    jobPage = requests.get(url)
    jobSoup = bs(jobPage.content, "html.parser")
    
    #Isolate text from the html and store in a list of words
    jobText = jobSoup.get_text().split()
    #Preprocess text to ease matching
    for i in range(len(jobText)):
        jobText[i] = jobText[i].lower()
        
    #Look for matches in each job description
    matches = ["eligible", "eligibility", "visa", "citizen", "citizenship"]
    for word in jobText:
        if word in matches:
            result[index] = True
            break
